To the residents of the P. O. Pedersen Dormitory,

The Traffic Committee hereby announces a bike raid on {{ .DateWithWeekdayEN }}.


LACK OF ROOM IN THE BIKE SHEDS

As several of you may have experienced, it is sometimes difficult to find room for your bike in the dormitory's bike sheds, meaning that you have to park your bike up against the shed instead.

The problem has multiple causes, among others are the following:
* Bikes are poorly positioned, taking up too much room.
* The sheds contain bikes that are unusable, or simply do not belong to the dormitory’s residents.
* Parked bikes must be usable (see §51, Section 2 of the House Regulations), to avoid a situation where the sheds become recycling centers with broken/half bikes.

It is stressed that the residents' guests are allowed to keep their bikes in the shed, provided, of course, that they do not store them there for months on end.


BIKE RAID

The Traffic Committee is responsible for the clean-up of the dormitory's outdoor areas, primarily in the bike sheds, thereby solving the latter problem. The bike raid is carried out according to §51 of the House Regulations. 

The bike raid was announced today ({{ .NoticeEN }}), according to §51, Section 2 of the House Regulations, with notices posted on the council board and on all kitchen doors plus through this e-mail.

This year’s bike raid is conducted like last year's as follows:

1) Two weeks before the bike raid, green threads are attached to the handlebars of all bikes in and around the bike sheds.
2) It is then the responsibility of the owner of each bike to remove this thread before the bike raid is carried out, as an indication that the bike is in use.
3) On the day of the raid all bikes still marked by threads will be removed by the Traffic Committee.

All bikes that still have the green thread attached to their handlebars when the raid is conducted, will be moved to a suitable location at the dormitory, where they will be chained and locked together. Hereafter, you can only get your bike back by contacting the inspector's office (the Traffic Committee is only responsible for the raid and do not have a key for the locks). Two weeks after the raid the police pick up the remaining removed bikes, primarily to investigate if any of them are stolen. Thus, there is no possibility of getting a free bike or free spare parts from the removed bikes.


ONE BIKE PER RESIDENT

The residents of the dormitory may only have one bike stored in the bike areas (see the House Regulations section 49). Only under special circumstances can the Traffic Committee grant dispensation from this rule. Old bikes should always be removed by the owner to free space in the bike sheds when they are no longer in use, i.e., when moving out, etc. It is unsustainable for all parties involved just to wait for the bike to be removed by others.


SPECIAL INFORMATION

Neighbors: Everyone is asked to remind their neighbors about the bike raid, especially if some do not read their mail, dormitory e-mails, and kitchen door notes. If you have a neighbor who is away from now and until after the bike raid, it may be necessary for you to remove the green thread for him/her.
Total safety: If you are very nervous about the bike raid, you are free to just keep your bike indoors on the day of the raid.
The locked room: The bike raid does not cover the locked room in the shed outside block 2.

